From: Keith Busch <kbusch@kernel.org>
Date: Tue, 10 Feb 2026 09:26:54 -0800
Subject: nvme-pci: ensure we're polling a polled queue
Patch-mainline: v7.0-rc3
Git-commit: 166e31d7dbf6aa44829b98aa446bda5c9580f12a
References: git-fixes

A user can change the polled queue count at run time. There's a brief
window during a reset where a hipri task may try to poll that queue
before the block layer has updated the queue maps, which would race with
the now interrupt driven queue and may cause double completions.

Reviewed-by: Christoph Hellwig <hch@lst.de>
Reviewed-by: Kanchan Joshi <joshi.k@samsung.com>
Signed-off-by: Keith Busch <kbusch@kernel.org>
Acked-by: Daniel Wagner <dwagner@suse.de>
---
 drivers/nvme/host/pci.c |    3 ++-
 1 file changed, 2 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

--- a/drivers/nvme/host/pci.c
+++ b/drivers/nvme/host/pci.c
@@ -1261,7 +1261,8 @@ static int nvme_poll(struct blk_mq_hw_ct
 	struct nvme_queue *nvmeq = hctx->driver_data;
 	bool found;
 
-	if (!nvme_cqe_pending(nvmeq))
+	if (!test_bit(NVMEQ_POLLED, &nvmeq->flags) ||
+	    !nvme_cqe_pending(nvmeq))
 		return 0;
 
 	spin_lock(&nvmeq->cq_poll_lock);
